column1: a few things about me that aren't always visible on the surface :
- i am an absolute moon lover and i always dreamt of having my own house one day where i have a huge sky light to watch the moon and stars at night.
- nature is my safe haven. i can retreat to it for weeks with no cell phone
column2: laptop or any other electronics and be content.

column1: - you won't see me cry often
column2: i just don't like doing that. especially in front of people.

column1: - but surround me with gem stones
column2: rocks and geode's...you might see my teary eyes as i keep saying over and over subhanallah
column4: subhanallah... allah swt is so great!

column1: - as a kid i loved climbing trees! these days when i see a tree i have to fight my urge to climb one. i am not as flexible like i used to be anymore lol.
- i was sexually assaulted and i still fight with that traumatic experience. important movements such as #timesup and #metoo often trigger the flashbacks. some days are tougher than others.
- i have attempted suicide multiple times. but my angel
column3: was always the reason that i knocked sense back into myself. honestly
column4: i wanted to live so desperately
column5: but i didn't know anymore how.

column1: - i seem super awkward and quiet. but honestly
column2: i'm just selective to whom i show my true colours. because i'm a fucking delight to be around! - my talent is reading people. sometimes. when i look someone in the eye i can see the life they had before meeting me.

column1: - i shaved off all of my hair once
column2: at least once a day i think about doing it again :)
you might think : ""this girl shares too much of her life and processes on the internet!"" but in reality...that barely covers a 10% of what's going on in my head!

column1: تحدث الممثل #ماساكي_سودا في برنامج 'gyoretsu no dekiru horitsu sodanjo' عن تحرش المعجبات به، حيث قال انه كان في الخارج في احد الايام ورصدنه معجبات كبيرات في السن واستمررن بالصراخ وبعدها قاموا بعناقه ولمس وجهه رغما عنه وفكر في تلك اللحظة ""إذا كان رجل كبير السن يعانق فتاة صغيرة ، فإنه سيعتبر بالتأكيد تحرشًا جنسيًا ، ومع ذلك ، هل هو جيد إذا كانت مرأة من تفعل هذا؟"" ثم قال : اليست جريمة ان يأتي شخص فجأة تأتي ويقوم بمعانقتك؟
أجاب المحامي هارو كيتامورا: ""إنه في الأساس عمل إجرامي""، وعلق قائلاً: ""إنها ليست مشكلة إذا أعطى الشخص موافقته ولكن عندما يفعل الشخص هذا دون موافقة فإنه يصبح هجومًا/تحرشًا"".
1- لماذا السيدات الكبيرات يكونون مجنونات؟ من المؤسف انك ان تستطيع رفضهم بسبب صورتك كفنان
2- الا يقوم الفنانيين باحداث المصافحة لتجنب مثل هذه الحوادث
3- على الفنانيين ان يكونوا اكثر صرامة مع المعجبين هناك حقا أولئك الاوتاكو الحمقى الذين يتصرفون كما لو ان المشهور ملك لهم
4- كنت ساصرخ عليهم على الفور لو قام أحدهم فجأة بعناقي ولمس وجهي
5- لجميع من يقول انه أيضا مخطئ لانه سمح لهم وكان عليه الحديث اذا اوقفهم ستنتهي صورته ستقولون انه متكبر وان عليه شكر المعجبين الذين يجعلوه يكسب المال وتبدؤون بالتمر عليه
6- كانجاني اوكورا تحدث أيضا عن شي مشابه يحدث له
7- أولئك الجدات الجاهلات لو قام رجل فجأة بعناقك ولمسك هل تعتقدون انه امر جيد لكنتم تحدثتم في كل مكان عن مدى قبح الذكور
8- بتأكيد هن من كانساي لذا لايعلمون شي عن التحضر أولئك الجدات القديمات
9- لماذا لو حدث نفس الشي مع ايدول أنثى ستقف معها كل النساء ويطلبون بمعاقبة الرجال بينما لايحدث شي عندما يكون الفنان رجل!!
10- لماذا لاتعبرونه تحرش جنسي اذا قامت المرأة بالتهجم على الرجل هذا أمر شائع ولكن لا أحد يصنفه بهذا الشكل لماذا؟! لنقم نحن الرجال بعمل حركة مشابهة ل #metoo لضمان حقوقنا";;en;#اخبار_جي_اكتور

i wish you had not felt the only way out of your pain was to end your life.
i wish you knew how much you were loved.

i wish i could have been there for you at your darkest moments.
i wish you had not felt the only way out of your pain was to end your life.
i wish you knew how much you were loved.
anthony... you may be gone but not forgotten. years since that tragic day has passed but you are still pa of our story
until i see you again. ❤️ uicidesucks

column1: 207085;instagram;2019-02-10 14:41:07;FALSE;"long before the “break-up” that fueled my fire... -
i was a student in college
column2: who had grown tired of sports. i was a gymnast since age 5. i competed in gymnastics
column4: track and softball until the age of 18. -

column3: i just wanted to “have fun.” i received offers to move forward at the collegiate level but turned them down. -

column4: which was consuming in itself. until one night
column5: my party mentality backfired. i was taken advantage of. yes

column1: this ultimately was devastating at first. i honestly didn’t know what to think of myself or the situation. i didn’t even tell my family in fear they would think i was crazy. after all
column2: i lived in south dakota. that stuff just “doesn’t happen.” -

column1: i began eating my feelings until one afternoon i found myself in the drive thru at culver’s
column2: just balling my eyes out. “what am i doing?”-

column1: i began running long distance and striving to find the girl i once was. i’m not sure if i was running from the pain
column2: but nonetheless i wanted to change and beat this thing that was breaking me. i felt and believed i wasn’t good enough.

column1: i then moved to florida for a change. i began meeting great people at my new job. i ran two half marathons
column2: tore my meniscus and met that someone who fueled my now bodybuilding fire. he cheated and here we are... -
you will be okay. every obstacle prepares you for your next chapter. it’s up to you to notice when the universe is guiding you into your best self. keep moving forward!

韓国の男尊女卑が、思っていたよりすごいものだということ。もはや男尊女卑というレベルではなく、「女卑」という発想すら無い社会であることを感じました。82年生まれのジヨンがそうであるなら、全然過去の話ではない。
そういう、韓国に残る思想を知るにはとても良い本。具体的で生々しい。同じ女として、とても悔しい気持ちも起こる。

column2: we're celebrating buffalo native beverly johnson
column3: the groundbreaking supermodel who helped fuel the #metoo movement.

helped create a national avalanche of attention to sexual assault when she publicly shared her own allegations of being drugged at home of entertainment mogul bill cosby via a cup of cappuccino. but before her pivotal first-person piece in vanity fair in 2014
column4: and before she became the first black model to make it to the cover of vogue in the u.s. and elle in france
column5: johnson was a star swimmer in the queen city. in fact
column6: she almost made it to the olympics.

column1: johnson attended buffalo's bennett high school
column2: the same school as late entertainer rick james
column4: winning a number of swimming championships. she came close to making the u.s. national team in the 100-yard freestyle for the 1968 olympics in mexico city.

column2: johnson went on to northeastern university in boston on a full scholarship with the intent of becoming a lawyer
column3: but friends convinced her to try modeling. in the 1970s
column4: she moved to new york city to try her luck. one day
column5: she walked into the offices of glamour magazine and they hired her on the spot for a photo shoot. by the mid 1970s
column6: johnson was in heavy demand. she appeared on the cover of the u.s. version of vogue in august 1974 and the french edition of elle a year later.

column2: vanity fair published a first-person piece by johnson describing how cosby
column4: served her cappuccino laced with drugs during a visit at his home in the 1980s to audition for a role on the cosby show. she recognized what was happening
column8: prompting cosby to wordlessly pull her outside and shove her into a taxi.

column1: wrote johnson in vanity fair: ""i had to use my voice as a sister
column3: and as a woman who knows that
column5: nearly one in five women has been sexually assaulted at some time in her life
column6: that women of color face an even higher attack rate."" #blackhistorymonth2019 #buffaloblackhistory (photos courtesy grosvenor room genealogy; alchetron)";;en;#MeToo

column1: 207198;instagram;2019-02-10 16:29:59;FALSE;"ahh..okay i’m a little late to this and i know that i originally wasn’t gonna post this anyways but as of late i have seen the way #metoo women have been treated or disregarded. i will say something i have known a woman/girl to lie about sexual assault and harassment because of whatever reason
column2: but at the same time there are lots of women i know even personally that have in some way been sexually harassed and or assaulted in some way
column3: but for so long were afraid to speak up about it b/c of the back lash it can and has caused other women in the past. for example i was sexually assaulted a couple years ago and i held i in for so long and finally i told my parents and then my parents took me to tell the local pd and i did and in my interview with an svu detective he asked me “did you do anything that would lead him to think touching you was okay?” as if it were my fault someone i trusted violated my trust and sexually assaulted me he then convinced me that i had no case and that id be better off not going to court because after all boys will be boys
column4: little did he know i had been r*ped twice prior to that so even being harassed in such a minor way compared to full on r*ped but it had been so long ago that i didn’t bring it up because after all this time what was the point?

column1: my point being please..if i woman is saying that she had been sexually assaulted or harassed and the timeline for it was ‘so long ago’ please don’t immediately discredit them because it can take a long time to come to terms with something so horrible and terrible. it can take a long time to be able to just say it out loud to yourself let alone to the world and to a jury. #metoo #feminist #loveyourself";;en;#metoo

column1: we see this most evidently in the #metoo movement as brave women have used their voices in powerful ways to call the men that wronged them to accountability for their actions. but it also exists in the nooks and crannies of mundane work life. i’ve been in countless situations where my voice and perspective were not being respected or were just plain ignored

column1: 207206;instagram;2019-02-10 16:34:59;TRUE;;"and this is very important step one must take in their lives. just leave behind all the toxicity and negativity. be blunt and cut off. 🔥
step 13 of our #16stepprogram - how boys and men can step up for #metoo
cut out toxic friendships and relationships from your own life.
let’s recognise that abusive relationships affect men’s mental health and life as well. these relationships come in different forms
column2: from intimate partners to family and friends. learn to pick up on signs of abuse in relationships and friendships that leave you mentally and emotionally drained. all forms of abuse are cyclical and this is how you can to break the chain. ~in collaboration with @thepixelproject

column1: 207208;instagram;2019-02-10 16:35:22;FALSE;"today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn’t part from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

column1: تتعرض الراهبات في أديرة الفاتيكان إلى اغتصابات واعتداءات وصلت للعبودية الجنسية بحقهن وبالرغم من علم الكنيسة الكاثوليكية إلا أن الأمر لم يتوقف، هذا ما صرح به بابا الفاتيكان أثناء زيارته للإمارات.

فقبل اعترافه بالأمر في الإمارات، نشرت مجلة «نساء الكنائس في العالم» أن هؤلاء الراهبات أجبرن على الإجهاض، برغم أن هذا الأمر تحرمه الكنيسة الكاثوليكية، ولكن ”ثقافة الصمت والسرية“ الموجودة داخل الكنائس جعلت الراهبات يتخوفن من البوح عما يتعرضن له.
يُذكر أن حركة #metoo العالمية شجعت الراهبات على كشف هذه الانتهاكات الجنسية.
سابقًا أضطر سلفه البابا بندكتوس السادس عشر لإغلاق دير للراهبات بالكامل، عقب تعرضهن للإغتصاب على أيدي الكهنة. وتم توقيف بعض هؤلاء الكهنة.

column1: 207224;instagram;2019-02-10 17:01:37;FALSE;"the government has launched a consultation into the 3 month time limit to raise a tribunal claim for pregnant women and new mums - we need your help.

this is our chance to shout as loud as we can that women need greater access to justice. the idea that pregnant women and new mums can start a tribunal process within 3 months is utter insanity and it results in 0.6% of victims raising a claim. i was sacked when i was 4 months pregnant and a week later i discovered i was having a high risk pregnancy. the doctor said to me: 'whatever you do
column2: dont get stressed.' the 3 month time limit forced me to choose between the health of my baby and accessing the justice i deserved.

column2: a biology major with the end goal of working in human healthcare
column3: a survivor of sexual assault and abuse
column4: someone who has struggled with their body image and self-esteem for a very long time (largely due to misogyny/misogynoir and having my body hyper-sexualized in a variety of ways growing up)
column5: and especially someone with a vagina
column6: i think the ways in which we have conversations about vaginas matter. it’s still very taboo
column7: despite the fact that vaginas play a very relevant role in our daily lives
column8: from sex to child-bearing to menstruation. i admittedly didn’t know much about vagina monologues when i auditioned
column9: doing so mainly because wac encouraged me
column10: but after doing my research and being involved in this production
column11: i see that my thoughts and experiences are not isolated ones. we should not be ashamed of our bodies and genitalia
column12: and the ways in which they intertwine with our identities
column14: and health. i think this is an important play to start the much needed conversations we should be having. not only in this #metoo era
column15: but also in an age where we are more aware of its exclusive natures
column16: and how we are able to make said conversations change with the way our perceptions of gender

column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch

column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move

column1: writing is a therapeutic way to help heal after a toxic relationship. translating your thoughts into words can change how our brain thinks about things. writing also helps with sleep patterns
column3: and depression. and it's cheaper than therapy 😊 i have 3 forms of writings listed below. 💜journaling. journaling is a safe and private way to process the traumatic memories of your past relationship that you aren't ready to share with anyone else or say it aloud. you can even confront your ex in your journal. write him a letter in your journal saying everything you wish you could tell him. destroying the letter afterwards can also feel liberating. 💜blogging. when you create a blog
column4: that means you are ready to share with the world your thoughts
column6: your struggles and your accomplishments. it's also a great way to spread awareness
column8: and education. 🗣check out my latest blog at www.zjkprosperousgroup.com/blog 💜writing a book. becoming an author will help teach you the unique valve of your own willpower. it can be fiction or non-fiction. your choice! writing a book forces you to leave your comfort zone. leaving your comfort zone promotes growth. i have tackled journaling and blogging. now it's time i become an author. 💪🏽

column1: day 7 ~  tarana burke is a civil rights activist and is the founder of the #metoomovement! the me too movement raises awareness of sexual abuse and assault in the country and in the world. she also founded just be inc which is an organization that promotes wellness of young females of color. she is also the senior director of girls for gender equality in brooklyn which is an organization that helps support the development and skills of young girls of color. she has won many awards and honors for her work including being named time’s person of the year. i appreciate all of her work she has done to support and advocate for young girls and women. today tarana burke
column2: i honor you queen!!! 👑💖✨😘 thank you for your work! .

column1: 207420;instagram;2019-02-10 21:26:27;FALSE;"times may have changed but unfortunately the narrative has not. women have and still do face discrimination and are viewed as having little credibility when it comes to truth telling. why do you think our culture still allows this to happen? if someone speaks their truth
column2: especially in instances of rape/sexual assault or harassment
column3: it is our job to not only believe them but to support them. trauma is real and it is damaging to the human psyche and spirit. how can we expect women and other survivors to heal when their truth is denied?

column1: 207423;instagram;2019-02-10 21:28:11;FALSE;"celebration of service and survival is quickly approaching! our next woman of distinction to highlight is julie la “valle” jones.
julie has been involved in issues impacting women and girls since the 1970’s when she was in college at george washington university and co-founded and led my sister’s place
column4: education and advocacy program serving women and children living in violent homes in washington dc. jones was instrumental in organizing the first national meeting on domestic violence at the white house in 1977 and the first hearings on domestic violence by the us commission on civil rights (usccr) in 1978. today’s national coalition on domestic violence was formed by grassroots participants at the usccr hearings

column1: 207442;instagram;2019-02-10 21:37:14;FALSE;"🛑do carbs & calories give you anxiety? do you think you have to do endless hours of cardio? .
🚫i don’t count calories 📓 🚫i don’t spend hours at a gym
🚫i eat carbs—>3x/day—>every day! 🍠 🚫i eat fruit 🍉 🚫no weighing my food ⚖️
🚫no worry about “what do i do after this” because it’s a lifestyle and one i can absolutely maintain
so many {women especially} who are very afraid to eat too many calories or carbs {at all}
😥it makes me sad to know that so many feel so trapped by restricting themselves
column2: especially when these thoughts may actually be preventing them from reaching their goals.

column1: i have been eating more food than i have in years and seeing some amazing results!! if you want to learn more about how to eat
column2: not starve and get results let’s chat!!

column1: 207451;instagram;2019-02-10 21:52:37;FALSE;"😉to anyone still confused as to why gillette has to make commercials about true masculinity... today i was harassed in a walmart parking lot by several men who decided it would be ok to drive slowly past me as i was walking to my car and start shouting at me
column2: “hey what you doin tonight!! hey hey hey”. until i physically had to walk away from their vehicle. 🤨

i got in my car and drove around to where they had parked and had been watching me get into my vehicle. i took out my phone and started to take photos of their license plate.📸📸📸 i have never seen a group of grown men drive off so fast!😂 men:

column1: women don’t appreciate this type of behavior. and this is the quickest way to loose all respect. you may never remember our faces again
column2: but if we see you in public again
column3: rest assured we would never approach you for a “good time”. and to the ones who’ve learned to respect women as people

column1: there is nothing wrong with sticking up for yourself. be smart
column2: don’t ever be alone with someone who is harassing you. if you are ever in that situation
column3: start a voice memo on your phone(so they don’t see you recording) and get to a more populated area as soon as possible.

column1: you are not being “rude” for not smiling back or uncomfortably laughing at these actions. 🤔to the group of men who thought this was ok:
i’m choosing to not post your plate number. the internet is a scary place. people can find where you live
column3: and your family. regardless of how humiliating your behavior was
column4: i don’t wish that on you. i believe humans including myself can learn from mistakes.

column1: i also got a good laugh from watching you scramble to get out of the parking lot. i might be nice
share this post if you agee✨
also the photo of me is from last june. their truck didn’t match my aesthetic so it’s on the >>> 😂😂😂 #thankyounext

column2: and i thought i would share some thoughts for the single ladies in the room. ♥️ sometimes being single sucks. there are people (mostly married people) who will tell you not to rush it and enjoy this season. those people 🤬. ♥️ don’t get me wrong
column3: i l o v e my alone time. i am happy by myself. i am good at being alone. but i don’t want to be perpetually alone. i want a partner
column5: someone who loves me even though i can quote all seasons of gilmore girls. ♥️ i don’t have any answers as to why the crazy girl has been married seven times
column6: and i can’t find one. and i think not knowing is okay. i think you can simultaneously be very happy with everything you bring to the table and still long for your person.

column4: и постоянно ждёшь несуществующего «однажды». а надо не #ждать
column6: что каждый день приносит тебе шанс. шанс жить. шанс любить и верить. #шанс понять и принять. #улыбаться
column11: одеть очень красивое и смелое платье

column28: а не готовится к этому всю жизнь… и не искать поводов для счастья
column29: когда наступает новый день… ты не начинаешь новую #жизнь с утра

column1: 207550;instagram;2019-02-11 00:20:06;FALSE;not the most flattering picture not the most flattering shirt 😂. but i had to face a lot of unflattering truths about myself & about my experiences with sexual abuse. i had to get raw & naked with myself about my truth and it has been one of the most difficult wounds i’ve had to heal through. there was a moment in my healing journey that my denial just crumbled right before me. i got a huge slap on the face about my experiences
column3: my truth about sexual abuse. i got hit with the realization of how much the sexual abuse had affected my life
column5: my relationships. [[i mean it has completely re-structured my brain. think about it getting sexually abused & doing things against your will that you don’t understand at age 4 all the way through to age 12. during the most crucial years of brain development i was forced to re-structure my brain in such a way so that i could survive what i endured. it has been difficult for me to create and sustain healthy relationships among other things.]] when my denial crumbled
column6: this was my breakthrough moment. this was the moment i needed to really begin to heal. i broke down
column7: i cried. i was angry. i went through an emotional roller coaster. & then the real healing began. you reach a point in your healing where you realize that your experiences & the effects it has on your life won’t “just go away” & you actually have to put in work! i can’t tell you how many times i wanted to just stop talking about my trauma and just live a “normal” life uninterrupted from flashbacks
column13: etc. but i realized that in order to live uninterrupted i had to do the work it takes to heal through my trauma. quitting wasn’t going to speed up my healing process. it’s not easy at all. it’s really hard. & it’s going  to get really bad before it gets better. but it’s worth it. you are worth it. it’s possible to live a life uninterrupted. it will take time but when you do the work in time you will heal. you are a survivor
column14: you’ve made it through some of the worse days of your life. you can do the work to heal. i’ve done it. & i continue to work to keep healing! you are not alone.;;en;;;;;;0;;thealienmermaid;ıll ᑭᔕYᑕᕼIᑕ ᗩᒪíEᑎ ᗰEᖇᗰᗩIᗪ llı;;0;False;13;0;0;110;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ec02587ae6c41beebe3fc85335e3c00b/5D092BE2/t51.2885-15/e35/50539759_621974244911530_7260394367761815796_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;not the most flattering picture not the most flattering shirt 😂. but i had to face a lot of unflattering truths about myself & about my experiences with sexual abuse. i had to get raw & naked with myself about my truth and it has been one of the most difficult wounds i’ve had to heal through. there was a moment in my healing journey that my denial just crumbled right before me. i got a huge slap on the face about my experiences

column1: i’ve been here. in fact i think i spent a solid portion of my adult life with repressed anger.
one day i felt safe enough to tune into that anger. it was scary. it was overwhelming and felt like a bottomless pit of rage.
our bodies and brains are amazing. they can create entire systems through neuro pathways of the 🧠
healing then becomes a process of releasing into the underlying feeling of that anger. resulting in a chemical reaction that fires different neurones in the brain creating a new pathway.
there is no way to true healing without the surrender to the real emotion underneath.
surrender. not because you give up
column2: but because experiencing that grief will allow you to truly heal.

column1: 207566;instagram;2019-02-11 00:33:13;FALSE;"it is normal to want to feel better today.

for years i struggled feeling like i was so behind compared to others sexually. was my body broken? why can’t i orgasm? i was always in this rush to find an “easy button” to “fix” the problem and completely missed out on so much pleasure by avoiding being in the present.
stacey harris (aka @thewoodsyogi) is one of our healingher experts.  she is an absolute powerhouse in our program and helps women just like us
column2: on the daily.  as a psychotherapist who specializes in sex + yoga therapy
column3: she provides impactful tools for post-trauma growth.

column1: stacey reminds us of the importance to slow it down and take one sip at a time
column2: like your favourite cup of coffee.  this should be our avenue in healing
column3: taking one sip at a time and enjoying the ritual.  beyond grateful for beautiful souls who make our platform so special! we love you. #healingher

column1: 207570;instagram;2019-02-11 00:49:03;FALSE;"2020's democratic primary is looking like it's going to be a very interesting primary season. so far 10 candidates we know have jumped in that i know about. here is my stance on all of them. part one!

column2: i don't see how she can win a general election against donald trump. she's too easy to mock
column4: and the recent thing showing she identified as a native american is going to hurt her chances. at most
column5: i can see her getting 249 electoral votes against trump. she's known to undeperform races
column6: especially in 2018. she performed slightly worse than clinton did in 2016 in terms of margin
column7: and the republican governor won with nearly 67% of the vote compared to her nearly 61%. she's too polarizing as well
column8: and would be a terrible pick as the nominee. hard no on her.

column1: senator from new york. while just an exploratory committee
column2: she's likely to jump in the race. she managed to weaponize #metoo and use it against her colleague al franken
column4: without due process. she's hated by many democrats as well because of that. i frankly don't think she'd beat trump either. i'm a hard no

column1: senator from california. mixed bag in my opinion. before klobuchar jumped in she was my second choice
column3: but i think she has a shot  against trump. should she win the nomination
column4: she might moderate on things like medicare for all
column6: like a public option. if she does that

column2: indiana. would be first milennial and openly gay president if elected. he is a meh for me.

and is running on universal basic income

column1: 207589;instagram;2019-02-11 01:17:05;FALSE;today was my last day of training at rainn headquarters and i have to say that my heart is heavy as i leave. words will never be enough to share what an impact these past two days have made on my life. i feel so blessed to have been able to have the opportunity to meet so many incredible people
column2: including other survivors. sometimes it’s easy to get caught up in a world where many people are bystanders who do nothing when a crisis occurs
column3: or filled with naysayers who don’t believe it’s our job to change the world. this weekend has enabled me to meet likeminded individuals who are passionate about helping others
column4: and that alone has brought me an enormous amount of joy. i am incredibly grateful to have the chance to help others through rainn
column5: an organization that saved me when i was in a time of crisis. i’m always here for anyone who needs to talk
column6: but rainn is an amazing resource that i encourage all survivors of sexual violence (and their loved ones) to check out. thank you to everyone who has encouraged me to follow my dreams and supported me through my struggles. none of this would have been possible without your help. #metoo #rainn;;en;#metoo

column1: he forced this womanly child to break her bloom before the time had come

column2: that pure virgin soul was her's... forever more

column1: 207650;instagram;2019-02-11 02:33:34;FALSE;i have a headache. i am dizzy. have no emotions. a friend whose background is not so far off as mine was found in an alley. she od need the drugs she used was laced with fentanyl. the people she was with dumped in the alley. she wanted so bad to be good to be sober. her demons to big. i sit here and think that that could’ve been me but it not me.i don’t do drugs
column2: i could of been her bc of our backgrounds. but i’m stronger.my heart hurts. i feel numb. i feel all my parts are scrambling around because they don’t know what to do. so i drew. and now i right. i hope she’s in her happy place now. i hope i don’t have bad dreams. when i draw i feel better 💔 long. see?! #childabuse #complex #complexposttraumaticstressdisorder #cptsd #cptsdawareness #survivor #metoo #arttherapy #innersystem #thisisme #did #drawings #disassociativeidentitydisorderart #disassociativeidentitydisorder #healingwithart #cptsdartwork #cptsdlifestory #traumatherapy #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth  #myartwork #revovery #eyes #thebodykeepsthescore #couldofbeenme #butitsnotyou #ihavedid #fentanyl #fentanylod #fentanyoverdose;;en;#childabuse

column1: 207665;instagram;2019-02-11 02:46:40;FALSE;"“pain shapes a women into a warrior”- @r.h.sin
so vividly i remember the first time i read these words. the night after i first spoke with the police
column2: i was sitting outside in the cold trying to process what was happening. trying to wrap my mind around that the words “sexual assault” now applied to me.  i remember wondering if i’d ever feel like a warrior over this situation. it’s true what they say
column3: you don’t know your own strength until being strong is your only choice.

column1: i don’t even know the person i was a year ago. fear has faded into the desire to fight. moving forward
column2: i know that no matter what transpires during my case
column3: i am stronger than his actions.

column1: 207676;instagram;2019-02-11 03:20:26;FALSE;"living for others... the past 2 years has taught me the most important lesson of my life. to live for me... being raised as the preachers daughter
column2: i was never taught self expression or that it was even ok to be me. there were strict rules on who i was supposed to be at all times. so when i left the church at 18 i clung to one boyfriend after another who would dictate to me who i was. so desperate for love and affirmation i morphed into whoever they required me to be. i died my hair black for my foreign boyfriend
column3: platinum blonde for the one who liked blondes
column4: wore boots for the guy who wanted boots
column5: red lippy for the guy who wanted red lippy. hell i even tried to be a surfy chic for the surfer dude when i can't even swim. it was so ridiculous and it led to some pretty awful situations.

column1: it wasn't until one of these over controlling partners nearly killed me that i realized things had to change. i had to start living for me.
a couple years and countless therapy appointments later i've come out of my shell and out of the closet
column2: and am living my best life. the last pic is of me now
column5: i don't know if you can see it but i know the happiness in my eyes and i'm so grateful that i've learnt to live for me.

step 15 of our #16stepprogram - how boys and men can step up for #metoo.

column2: there is nothing wrong in being associated with anything deemed ‘girlie’. secondly
column6: and empathy are neither gender-specific nor do they have to be. turn up your empathy levels and challenge the world to not view and treat different genders unequally. apathy and indifference by men only add to the culture of violence. challenge this silent kind of abuse by imbuing compassion into your everyday dealings with people. ~in collaboration with @thepixelproject

column1: because i was in shock at the time.
i spoke to a san diego sorority about sexual assault and anxiety one year ago this week.
i spent dozens of hours preparing for this.
including several visits to the college campus.
hired a photographer to help spread the healing message through social media.
i left the night of the talk overflowing with gratitude
cried tears of purpose and joy on my walk out to the parking lot.
felt super connected to the spirit of the universe and my life purpose.
the sorority sister who had me come speak wrote me an email.
she said she was profoundly upset and disturbed by the content of my talk.
she said she was speaking on behalf of all of the sisters.
that my suggesting mindfulness and deep breathing could alleviate symptoms of anxiety was blatantly untrue.
she said my tips never worked for her 💔
one third of the ladies raised their hands saying they have panic attacks.
and one of them is telling me something that truly helps is blatantly untrue.
but this is how our nervous system works i thought..

column3: it's the parasympathetic nervous system... it baffled me for awhile
column4: how this could be her truth.

column1: i knew some of the ladies resonated with my talk
column2: i could see their heads nod as i spoke of anxiety and potential solutions.

column1: but worse yet i had my ted talk coming up in a month at another college campus on the same topic.

column3: how can i change my talk so that it didn't offend the people it's intended to help... like still share the truth but in a way that can be heard.. i prayed hard.

column1: then it occurred to me if i stuck with my story
and not a ""5 steps to solve your problem"" approach

column3: the people i felt called to help

column1: i am so grateful for what i learned that night at the sorority...
my own big lesson in how to be heard
i completely rewrote my ted talk.

that my suggesting mindfulness and deep breathing could alleviate symptoms of anxiety was blatantly untrue.
she said my tips never worked for her 💔
one third of the ladies raised their hands saying they have panic attacks.
and one of them is telling me something that truly helps is blatantly untrue.
but this is how our nervous system works i thought..

column3: it is the parasympathetic nervous system... it baffled me for awhile
column4: how this could be her truth.

column1: i knew some of the ladies resonated with my talk
column2: i could see their heads nod as i spoke of anxiety and potential solutions.

column1: but worse yet i had my ted talk coming up in a month at another college campus on the same topic.

column3: how can i change my talk so that it didn't offend the people it is intended to help... like still share the truth but in a way that can be heard.. i prayed hard.

column1: then it occurred to me if i stuck with my story
and not a ""5 steps to solve your problem"" approach

column3: the people i felt called to help

column1: i am so grateful for what i learned that night at the sorority...
my own big lesson in how to be heard
i completely rewrote my ted talk.
continues in comments 👇🏽";"i never mentioned this to you...
because i was in shock at the time.
i spoke to a san diego sorority about sexual assault and anxiety one year ago this week.
i spent dozens of hours preparing for this.
including several visits to the college campus.
hired a photographer to help spread the healing message through social media.
i left the night of the talk overflowing with gratitude
cried tears of purpose and joy on my walk out to the parking lot.
felt super connected to the spirit of the universe and my life purpose.

column1: 韓国100万部ベストセラー✖︎映画化
そんな響きに面白さを期待して飛びついたら火傷した。
ちょうど韓国語の勉強や、韓国への関心が高まっていた時に書店で出会った。
この本は韓国の過去と現在の女性の境遇や差別、人権などを問題提起をするフェミニズム小説だ。
昨今me tooなど、女性が受けた不遇から目を背けず、声をあげようと世界で勢いづいてる時代から生まれた小説。小説というより社会学⁈ 直接的に言うより、小説にした方が社会問題って目を向けやすいのかも。
男性の意見なんて軽々しく言えたもんじゃないかもしれない。女性の境遇を理解し男性とか女性とか差別するのではなく、共生していくために考えていかなければならないと感じた。
ジヨンは夫の『気にする』『手伝う』という言葉に腹を立てた。育児を手伝ってあげる、家事を手伝う等、最初から女性がやるもんでしょみたいな風潮は気がついてないだけでたくさんあると思った。
何がベストセラーになる理由か気になっていたが、多く読まれてる理由は、キム•ジヨンは私だと、共感する女性が多いこと、またその祖母、母、娘の視点、男性でも女家族いる人なら読んでみようと話題になった。
映画化したら世界はどんな反応をするのだろう。
もうすぐ国際女性デーですね。
oecdによる、ガラスの天井指数(マイノリティや女性の昇進を妨げる、見えない壁)でも、韓国と日本は世界の最下位でガッカリした。
表紙の女性に表情が描かれていなかった理由は、そのキム•ジヨンこそ、あなたなのかもしれない。

#韓国 #韓国語勉強 #韓国旅行 #metoo #ママ虫
#国際女性デー #emawatson #ガラスの天井 #glassceiling #internationalwomensday #女性が輝けば世界が輝く #韓国ファッション #redvelvet #irene #本  #読書";;en;#82년생김지영

column1: 207971;instagram;2019-02-11 12:28:55;FALSE;"science and gender equality are both vital for the achievement of the internationally agreed development goals
column2: including the 2030 agenda for sustainable development. over the past 15 years
column3: the global community has made a lot of effort in inspiring and engaging women and girls in science. yet women and girls continue to be excluded from participating fully in science.

column2: less than 30 per cent of researchers worldwide are women. according to unesco data (2014 - 2016)
column3: only around 30 per cent of all female students select stem-related fields in higher education. globally
column4: female students’ enrolment is particularly low in ict (3 per cent)
column6: mathematics and statistics (5 per cent) and in engineering
column7: manufacturing and construction (8 per cent). long-standing biases and gender stereotypes are steering girls and women away from science related fields. as in the real world
column8: the world on screen reflects similar biases—the 2015 gender bias without borders study by the geena davis institute showed that of the onscreen characters with an identifiable stem job
